Subject: blank node

Subject: B cell
Value: Rectal cell, postembryonic blast cell in male

Subject: U cell
Value: Rectal cell, postembryonic blast cell in male

Subject: cell
Value: A material entity of anatomical origin (part of or deriving from an organism) that has as its parts a maximally connected cell compartment surrounded by a plasma membrane.

Subject: cell
Value: A material entity that has a plasma membrane and results from cellular division.

Subject: biological process
Value: A biological process is the execution of a genetically-encoded biological module or program. It consists of all the steps required to achieve the specific biological objective of the module. A biological process is accomplished by a particular set of molecular functions carried out by specific gene products (or macromolecular complexes), often in a highly regulated manner and in a particular temporal sequence.

Subject: biological process
Value: A process that emerges from two or more causally-connected macromolecular activities and has evolved to achieve a biological objective.

Subject: definition
Value:
2012-04-05: 
Barry Smith

The official OBI definition, explaining the meaning of a class or property: 'Shall be Aristotelian, formalized and normalized. Can be augmented with colloquial definitions'  is terrible.

Can you fix to something like:

A statement of necessary and sufficient conditions explaining the meaning of an expression referring to a class or property.

Alan Ruttenberg

Your proposed definition is a reasonable candidate, except that it is very common that necessary and sufficient conditions are not given. Mostly they are necessary, occasionally they are necessary and sufficient or just sufficient. Often they use terms that are not themselves defined and so they effectively can't be evaluated by those criteria. 

On the specifics of the proposed definition:

We don't have definitions of 'meaning' or 'expression' or 'property'. For 'reference' in the intended sense I think we use the term 'denotation'. For 'expression', I think we you mean symbol, or identifier. For 'meaning' it differs for class and property. For class we want documentation that let's the intended reader determine whether an entity is instance of the class, or not. For property we want documentation that let's the intended reader determine, given a pair of potential relata, whether the assertion that the relation holds is true. The 'intended reader' part suggests that we also specify who, we expect, would be able to understand the definition, and also generalizes over human and computer reader to include textual and logical definition. 

Personally, I am more comfortable weakening definition to documentation, with instructions as to what is desirable. 

We also have the outstanding issue of how to aim different definitions to different audiences. A clinical audience reading chebi wants a different sort of definition documentation/definition from a chemistry trained audience, and similarly there is a need for a definition that is adequate for an ontologist to work with.  @en

Subject: capable of
Value: A relation between a material entity (such as a cell) and a process, in which the material entity has the ability to carry out the process.

Subject: helper property (not for use in curation)
acts upstream of or within, positive effect
acts upstream of or within, negative effect
causally upstream of or within, negative effect
causally upstream of or within, positive effect
independent continuant
Value: b is an independent continuant = Def. b is a continuant which is such that there is no c and no t such that b s-depends_on c at t. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [017-002])@en

Subject: process
Value: p is a process = Def. p is an occurrent that has temporal proper parts and for some time t, p s-depends_on some material entity at t. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [083-003])@en

Subject: disposition
Value: b is a disposition means: b is a realizable entity & bs bearer is some material entity & b is such that if it ceases to exist, then its bearer is physically changed, & bs realization occurs when and because this bearer is in some special physical circumstances, & this realization occurs in virtue of the bearers physical make-up. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [062-002])@en

Subject: quality
Value: a quality is a specifically dependent continuant that, in contrast to roles and dispositions, does not require any further process in order to be realized. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [055-001])@en

Subject: characteristic
Value: b is a specifically dependent continuant = Def. b is a continuant & there is some independent continuant c which is not a spatial region and which is such that b s-depends_on c at every time t during the course of bs existence. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [050-003])@en

Subject: role
Value: b is a role means: b is a realizable entity & b exists because there is some single bearer that is in some special physical, social, or institutional set of circumstances in which this bearer does not have to be& b is not such that, if it ceases to exist, then the physical make-up of the bearer is thereby changed. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [061-001])@en

Subject: generically dependent continuant
Value: b is a generically dependent continuant = Def. b is a continuant that g-depends_on one or more other entities. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [074-001])@en

Subject: part_of
Value: a core relation that holds between a part and its whole@en

Subject: has part
Value: a core relation that holds between a whole and its part@en

Subject: preceded_by
Value: x is preceded by y if and only if the time point at which y ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which x starts. Formally: x preceded by y iff (y) <= (x), where  is a function that maps a process to a start point, and  is a function that maps a process to an end point.@en

Subject: precedes
Value: x precedes y if and only if the time point at which x ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: x precedes y iff (x) <= (y), where  is a function that maps a process to a start point, and  is a function that maps a process to an end point.@en

Subject: occurs in
Value: b occurs_in c =def b is a process and c is a material entity or immaterial entity& there exists a spatiotemporal region r and b occupies_spatiotemporal_region r.& forall(t) if b exists_at t then c exists_at t & there exist spatial regions s and s where & b spatially_projects_onto s at t& c is occupies_spatial_region s at t& s is a proper_continuant_part_of s at t@en

Subject: contains process
Value: [copied from inverse property 'occurs in'] b occurs_in c =def b is a process and c is a material entity or immaterial entity& there exists a spatiotemporal region r and b occupies_spatiotemporal_region r.& forall(t) if b exists_at t then c exists_at t & there exist spatial regions s and s where & b spatially_projects_onto s at t& c is occupies_spatial_region s at t& s is a proper_continuant_part_of s at t@en

Subject: lipid
Value: 'Lipids' is a loosely defined term for substances of biological origin that are soluble in nonpolar solvents. They consist of saponifiable lipids, such as glycerides (fats and oils) and phospholipids, as well as nonsaponifiable lipids, principally steroids.

Subject: characteristic of
Value: a relation between a specifically dependent continuant (the characteristic) and any other entity (the bearer), in which the characteristic depends on the bearer for its existence.@en

Subject: participates in
Value: a relation between a continuant and a process, in which the continuant is somehow involved in the process@en

Subject: has participant
Value: a relation between a process and a continuant, in which the continuant is somehow involved in the process@en

Subject: function of
Value: a relation between a function and an independent continuant (the bearer), in which the function specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: quality of
Value: a relation between a quality and an independent continuant (the bearer), in which the quality specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: role of
Value: a relation between a role and an independent continuant (the bearer), in which the role specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: has function
Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a function, in which the function specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: has quality
Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a quality, in which the quality specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: has role
Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a role, in which the role specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: has disposition
Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a disposition, in which the disposition specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: has component process
Value: w 'has process component' p if p and w are processes,  w 'has part' p and w is such that it can be directly disassembled into into n parts p, p2, p3, ..., pn, where these parts are of similar type.

Subject: overlaps
Value: x overlaps y if and only if there exists some z such that x has part z and z part of y

Subject: has component
Value: w 'has component' p if w 'has part' p and w is such that it can be directly disassembled into into n parts p, p2, p3, ..., pn, where these parts are of similar type.

Subject: develops from
Value: x develops from y if and only if either (a) x directly develops from y or (b) there exists some z such that x directly develops from z and z develops from y

Subject: regulates
Value: p regulates q iff p is causally upstream of q, the execution of p is not constant and varies according to specific conditions, and p influences the rate or magnitude of execution of q due to an effect either on some enabler of q or some enabler of a part of q.

Subject: negatively regulates
Value: p negatively regulates q iff p regulates q, and p decreases the rate or magnitude of execution of q.

Subject: positively regulates
Value: p positively regulates q iff p regulates q, and p increases the rate or magnitude of execution of q.

Subject: capable of part of
Value: c stands in this relationship to p if and only if there exists some p' such that c is capable_of p', and p' is part_of p.

Subject: has input
Value: p has input c iff: p is a process, c is a material entity, c is a participant in p, c is present at the start of p, and the state of c is modified during p.

Subject: has developmental contribution from
Value: x has developmental contribution from y iff x has some part z such that z develops from y@en

Subject: developmentally contributes to
Value: inverse of has developmental contribution from

Subject: acts upstream of
Value: c acts upstream of p if and only if c enables some f that is involved in p' and p' occurs chronologically before p, is not part of p, and affects the execution of p. c is a material entity and f, p, p' are processes.

Subject: acts upstream of or within
Value: c acts upstream of or within p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of or within p. c is a material entity and p is an process.

Subject: results in developmental progression of
Value: p results in the developmental progression of s iff p is a developmental process and s is an anatomical entity and p causes s to undergo a change in state at some point along its natural developmental cycle (this cycle starts with its formation, through the mature structure, and ends with its loss).

Subject: causally upstream of, positive effect
Value: p is causally upstream of, positive effect q iff p is casually upstream of q, and the execution of p is required for the execution of q.

Subject: causally upstream of, negative effect
Value: p is causally upstream of, negative effect q iff p is casually upstream of q, and the execution of p decreases the execution of q.

Subject: characteristic of part of
Value: q characteristic of part of w if and only if there exists some p such that q inheres in p and p part of w.

Subject: enables
Value: c enables p iff c is capable of p and c acts to execute p.

Subject: part of structure that is capable of
Value: this relation holds between c and p when c is part of some c', and c' is capable of p.

Subject: involved in
Value: c involved_in p if and only if c enables some process p', and p' is part of p

Subject: has developmental potential involving
Value: x has developmental potential involving y iff x is capable of a developmental process with output y. y may be the successor of x, or may be a different structure in the vicinity (as for example in the case of developmental induction).@en

Subject: has potential to developmentally contribute to
Value: x has potential to developmentrally contribute to y iff x developmentally contributes to y or x is capable of developmentally contributing to y@en

Subject: has potential to develop into
Value: x has the potential to develop into y iff x develops into y or if x is capable of developing into y@en

Subject: has potential to directly develop into
Value: x has potential to directly develop into y iff x directly develops into y or x is capable of directly developing into y@en

Subject: indirectly positively regulates
Value: p indirectly positively regulates q iff p is indirectly causally upstream of q and p positively regulates q.

Subject: indirectly negatively regulates
Value: p indirectly negatively regulates q iff p is indirectly causally upstream of q and p negatively regulates q.

Subject: causally related to
Value: relation that links two events, processes, states, or objects such that one event, process, state, or object (a cause) contributes to the production of another event, process, state, or object (an effect) where the cause is partly or wholly responsible for the effect, and the effect is partly or wholly dependent on the cause.

Subject: causally upstream of
Value: p is causally upstream of q iff p is causally related to q, the end of p precedes the end of q, and p is not an occurrent part of q.

Subject: immediately causally upstream of
Value: p is immediately causally upstream of q iff p is causally upstream of q, and the end of p is coincident with the beginning of q.

Subject: causally upstream of or within
Value: p is 'causally upstream or within' q iff p is causally related to q, and the end of p precedes, or is coincident with, the end of q.

Subject: causally downstream of or within
Value: inverse of causally upstream of or within

Subject: involved in regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' regulates some p

Subject: involved in positive regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' positively regulates some p

Subject: involved in negative regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' negatively regulates some p

Subject: involved in or involved in regulation of
Value: c involved in or regulates p if and only if either (i) c is involved in p or (ii) c is involved in regulation of p

Subject: is active in
Value: c executes activity in d if and only if c enables p and p occurs_in d.  Assuming no action at a distance by gene products, if a gene product enables (is capable of) a process that occurs in some structure, it must have at least some part in that structure.

Subject: has part that occurs in
Value: p has part that occurs in c if and only if there exists some p1, such that p has_part p1, and p1 occurs in c.

Subject: causal relation between processes
Value: p is causally related to q if and only if p or any part of p and q or any part of q are linked by a chain of events where each event pair is one where the execution of p influences the execution of q. p may be upstream, downstream, part of, or a container of q.

Subject: towards
Value: q towards e2 if and only if q is a relational quality such that q inheres-in some e, and e != e2 and q is dependent on e2

Subject: directly regulates
Value: p directly regulates q iff p is immediately causally upstream of q and p regulates q.

Subject: has part structure that is capable of
Value: s 'has part structure that is capable of' p if and only if there exists some part x such that s 'has part' x and x 'capable of' p

Subject: directly positively regulates
Value: p directly positively regulates q iff p is immediately causally upstream of q, and p positively regulates q.

Subject: directly negatively regulates
Value: p directly negatively regulates q iff p is immediately causally upstream of q, and p negatively regulates q.

Subject: acts upstream of, positive effect
Value: c 'acts upstream of, positive effect' p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of p, and the direction of f is positive

Subject: acts upstream of, negative effect
Value: c 'acts upstream of, negative effect' p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of p, and the direction of f is negative

Subject: indirectly causally upstream of
Value: p is indirectly causally upstream of q iff p is causally upstream of q and there exists some process r such that p is causally upstream of r and r is causally upstream of q.

Subject: indirectly regulates
Value: p indirectly regulates q iff p is indirectly causally upstream of q and p regulates q.

Subject: Lineage
Value: pedigree of nuclei, lineal descent from P0, the founder.

Subject: epithelial cell
Value: cell of epithelium, the layer of cells that cover the external surface of an organism as well as forming an inner lining between the tissues and organs of that organism and the external environment. In C. elegans epithelial cells include epithelium of the alimentary tract, intestinal cells, hypodermis, interfacial cells and somatic gonad cells.

Subject: marginal cell
Value: a type of pharyngeal cell that connects basement membrane to the apices of triangle-shaped pharyngeal lumen.

Subject: pharynx
Value: the feeding organ, a neuro-muscular pump in the head of the animal, used to ingest food, bacteria suspended in liquid, filter them out, grind them up and transport posteriorly into the instestine.

Subject: terminal bulb
Value: the last, posterior bulb of the pharynx.

Subject: corpus
Value: the first, anterior bulb of the pharynx.

Subject: isthmus
Value: a section of pharynx of which muscles contract with a peristaltic motion.

Subject: organ
Value: a collection of cells or cell groups that collectively perform a function

Subject: Cell
Value: a cellular object that consists of subcellular components, expresses genes or functions.

Subject: anchor cell
Value: anchor cell, induces vulva, part of hermaphrodite gonad.

Subject: excretory duct cell
Value: cell that forms the duct of the excretory system.

Subject: linker cell
Value: male gonad cell, leads gonad during morphogenesis and initiates union with cloaca

Subject: labial sensillum
Value: sensillum of inner or outer labial.

Subject: inner labial sensillum
Value: sensory organ of the inner labial.

Subject: gonad
Value: organ producing either sperm or ova.

Subject: GLR
Value: set of six cells that form a thin cylindrical sheet between pharynx and ring neuropile; no chemical synapses, but gap junctions with muscle arms and RME motor neurons, might be glial cells

Subject: hermaphrodite gonad
Value: organ in hermaphrodite animal that produces both ova and sperm.

Subject: dorso-rectal ganglion
Value: the ganglion that lies above and behind the rectum in the tail, in close continuity with the anal hypodermal ridge. It contains 3 neuron cell bodies (DVA, DVB and DVC) that send their neuronal processes into the ventral nerve cord via dorso-rectal commissures that encircle the anus. The ganglion contains no local neuropil in the hermaphrodite. In the adult male tail, this ganglion gains additional neurons and some local neuropil.

Subject: dorsal ganglion
Value: ganglion that lies beside the nerve ring in the head. It contains neuron cell bodies that send their neuronal processes into the ring and longitudinal nerves, but form no local neuropil separate from the nerve ring. The dorsal ganglion is in close contact with the dorsal hypodermal cord.

Subject: touch receptor neuron
Value: neurons that sense body touch, have specialized microtubules in processes.

Subject: buccal cavity
Value: cuticle-lined lumenal region surrounded by pharyngeal epithelium, situated at the anterior end of pharynx.

Subject: ventral ganglion
Value: ganglion lies beside the nerve ring in the head, just anterior of the retrovesicular ganglion. It contains about 20 interneuron and motorneuron cell bodies that all send their neuronal processes into the ring. The cell bodies are divided into two groups by the intrusion of the excretory duct and canal. The cells are bounded by a basal lamina which physically separates them from the lateral ganglion even though they are adjacent to one another.

Subject: spermatheca
Value: an accordion-like tube that contains sperm and is the site of oocyte fertilization.

Subject: body ganglion
Value: ganglion in the trunk of the body.

Subject: uterine muscle
Value: muscle lining of the uterine wall.

Subject: anterior ganglion
Value: ganglion anterior to the nerve ring

Subject: motor neuron
Value: neuron making synapse on an effector (muscle, gland).

Subject: phasmid sensillum
Value: bilateral sensory organ in the tail, similar to the amphid in the head.

Subject: phasmid left sensillum
Value: the left one in the pair of phasmid sensilla.

Subject: pharyngeal muscle cell
Value: type of cells that make up muscle layers in the pharynx.

Subject: posterior lateral ganglion
Value: ganglion on the lateral side, in postior portion of the body, associated with posterior deirid.

Subject: epithelial system
Value: lies within the body wall, in close relation to nervous system and excretory system.

Subject: muscular system
Value: the organ system that allows the animal move, includes all muscles.

Subject: body region
Value: region of the body by which tissues, cells or cell parts are classified

Subject: head
Value: anterior-most body region containing the pharynx.

Subject: midbody
Value: body region posterior to the head and anterior to the tail

Subject: tail
Value: posterior region, from rectum to the end

Subject: digestive tract
Value: inner tube of two concentric tubes that make up the body

Subject: Organ system
Value: intergrated group of organs, performing one or more unified functions.

Subject: Sex specific entity
Value: anatomical or cell objects that exist in only one, male or hermaphrodite, sex.

Subject: seam cell
Value: a group of hypodermal cells that lie along the apical midline of the hypodermis, at the extreme left and right sides between nose and tail

Subject: interfacial epithelial cell
Value: an epithelial cell that serves either to bridge two neighboring epithelial tissues or to form an opening in the epithelium.

Subject: cuticle
Value: a rigid external coating which is secreted by the hypodermis, seam and some transitional epithelial cells which covers the outer body, the major openings  into the body cavity from the exterior, and two large sensory bristles, the male spicules.  The cuticle of the spicules, the hook,  and of some portions of the spicule channels is especially rigid and is probably sclerotized.  Similar sclerotic features are occasionally noted in the ventral surface of the male tail fan.

Subject: male-specific anatomical entity
Value: cells or anatomical parts specific to the male sex

Subject: hermaphrodite-specific anatomical entity
Value: cells or anatomical parts specific to the hermaphrodite sex

Subject: sensory neuron
Value: neuron that senses external stimuli and transduce them to signals internal to the organism.

Subject: accessory cell
Value: cells that support sensory neurons, similar to glial cells in vertebrates. A category which collectively refers to socket cells, sheath cells, and structural cells, or their processes.  All of these cells extend long processes which serve a supporting role, rather like glia, to form a protective environment around sensory neuron endings.  In addition, some of these cells extend broad thin processes from their somata which wrap around neuronal ganglia, again in a glia-like fashion

Subject: Functional system
Value: concerns with functional aspects of cells and anatomical parts

Subject: Anatomy
Value: entity of anatomical origin that is either entirely acellular or is a collection of cells and acellular parts.

Subject: cloaca
Value: a feature of the male tail, caudal to the proctodeum, where the vas deferens and the intestine open out jointly near the tail tip to discharge their contents.

Subject: excretory gland cell
Value: gland cell of the secretory-excretory system, sends processes to ring, opens into excretory duct.

Subject: germ line
Value: cell line which early in development becomes differentiated from the remaining somatic cell line, and alone has the potential to undergo meiosis and form gametes.

Subject: intestinal cell
Value: any of 20 large epithelial cells which form a tube and are mostly situated as bilaterally symmetric pairs around the tubular lumen. Each of these cell pairs forms an intestinal ring ( II-IX int rings). The most anterior intestinal ring (int ring I), however, is made of four cells. Intestinal cells contain large nuclei with large nucleoli and numerous autofluorescent granules in their cytoplasm.

Subject: neuronal sheath cell
Value: a structural (glial) cell which forms an specialized environment surrounding the sensory ending(s) of one or more neurons; sometimes accompanied by a more distal socket cell.  In early development of the sensory nerves and of the nerve ring some sheath cells (cephalics and labials) may also provide a substrate for axon guidance

Subject: alimentary muscle
Value: muscle of the alimentary organ system.

Subject: gonadal sheath cell
Value: five pairs of thin gonadal sheath cells form a single layer covering the germ line component of each arm, each pair occupying a stereotyped position along the gonad proximal-distal axis.

Subject: ventral nerve cord
Value: a large process bundle that runs along the vental mid-line extending from the ventral region of the nerve ring.

Subject: nerve ring
Value: the most extensive region of neuropil in the animal, consists of a large toroidal bundle of processes.

Subject: dorsal nerve cord
Value: a bundle of nerve processes that runs along the dorsal mid-line of the animal.

Subject: head muscle
Value: body wall muscle in the head, including first eight cells of each muscle quadrants which are innervated by nerve ring neurons.

Subject: blast cell
Value: precursor cell destined to divide some time after hatching.

Subject: uterine-vulval cell
Value: monoucleate interfacial cell between the uterus and vulva (uv1-uv3), four sets total (L/R, A/P)

Subject: male gonad
Value: gonad of a male animal, produces sperm.

Subject: germ cell
Value: a cell, of either sex, directly concerned in the production of a new organism.

Subject: body wall muscle cell
Value: type of 95 cells that make up muscles of the body wall.

Subject: ciliated neuron
Value: neuron type, neurons that have ciliated nerve endings.

Subject: serotonergic neuron
Value: neuron that uses serotonin as a vesicular neurotransmitter.

Subject: cholinergic neuron
Value: neuron that uses vesicular acetylcholine as a neurotransmitter.

Subject: germline precursor cell
Value: member of a set of two cells that generate exclusively sperm and ovum.

Subject: distal tip cell
Value: somatic cell that situates at the tip of a gonad arm.

Subject: seminal vesicle
Value: part of male gonad that holds mature sperm, made of a total of 12 nuclei.

Subject: gubernacular muscle
Value: specialized muscle type in male sex organ.

Subject: longitudinal male muscle
Value: specialized muscle type in the posterior of adult male.

Subject: cephalic sensillum
Value: sensillum in the head, each with a CEP receptor neuron.

Subject: sensillum
Value: sensory organ, consists of sensory neurons and supporting cells.

Subject: ray
Value: male sensory organ; nine bilateral pairs of finger-like rays (numbered 1 to 9, Left/Right) radiate from the tail and are embedded in a cuticlar fan.

Subject: tail ganglion
Value: ganglion in the tail region (posterior to rectum).

Subject: embryonic cell
Value: cell that exists in and is part of an embryo.

Subject: post-embryonic cell
Value: a cell that is born in a worm after hatching.

Subject: vulval precursor cell
Value: cell that has the potential to form structural part of a vulva.

Subject: hermaphrodite somatic gonadal cell
Value: somatic (not germline) cell of the hermaphrodite gonad.

Subject: hypodermal cell
Value: primary cell type that forms the hypodermis.

Subject: syncytium precursor
Value: cell that is mononuclear and has a strong potential to fuse with other cell(s) to form a multinucleated cell.

Subject: syncytium
Value: cell that has more than one nucleus.

Subject: seminal vesical cell
Value: seminal vesicle cell of male gonad.

Subject: gon_male_sves Z1 or Z4
Value: seminal vesicle, outer; cell of the pedigree Z1.paapp or Z4.aaapp.

Subject: vulval syncytia precursor
Value: precursor cell of, before fusion to form vulval syncytia vulA(4), vulC(4), vulD(2), vulE(4) and vulF(4).

Subject: sex organ
Value: anatomical part of the body which is involved in sexual reproduction and constitutes the reproductive system.

Subject: male genital
Value: antomical structure of the male involved in sexual reproduction.

Subject: mechanosensory neuron
Value: neuron that senses and responds to mechanical stimuli, such as touch.

Subject: uterine epithelial cell
Value: cell of the epithelia of uterus.
